Client-server architecture is a network model in which multiple clients (users/devices) request services and resources from a centralized server.

Client: A device or application (like a web browser) that sends requests.
Server: A system that processes requests and sends responses.
Communication happens over the Internet using HTTP/HTTPS protocols.

Key Features
Centralized data management
Multiple clients can connect to one server
Easy maintenance and scalability

PROCEDURE OF OPENING A WEBSITE
User enters URL
Example: www.google.com in the browser
DNS Lookup
- Browser contacts DNS (Domain Name System)
Converts domain name into IP address
- Connection Established
Browser sends request to server using IP address
- Uses TCP/IP protocol
HTTP Request Sent
- Browser sends an HTTP/HTTPS request to the server
Server Processing
- Server receives request
- May interact with database to fetch data
HTTP Response
- Server sends response (HTML, CSS, JS files)
Browser Rendering
-Browser displays the webpage visually
